ForgeZero Preprocessor (FZP)

FZP is an internal preprocessing layer that can drive configuration values and generate generated headers as part of a normal build.

Supported directives

- #define NAME value
- #undef NAME
- #include "file.fz" or #include <stdio.h>
- #if expr
- #ifdef NAME
- #ifndef NAME
- #else
- #elif
- #endif
- #error "message"
- #pragma once

Automatic integration

A regular build automatically scans for template headers such as config.h.in and generates matching outputs. The preprocess step runs before source discovery, so projects can use generated headers without extra flags.

Config-driven preprocessing

Use a [preprocess] section in the ForgeZero config to declare explicit inputs and outputs:

[preprocess]
enabled = true
inputs = ["config.h.in"]
outputs = ["config.h"]

A complete example is available in testdata/fzp_project. The project contains:

- testdata/fzp_project/config.h.in with #define, conditional blocks, and a system-header include check.
- testdata/fzp_project/main.c that includes the generated header and prints the resulting macros.
- testdata/fzp_project/fz.toml defining the preprocessing step.

Running fz -dir . from that directory generates testdata/fzp_project/.fz_objs/include/config.h and builds the binary successfully.

Security and include resolution

- Absolute include paths are rejected unless they fall inside allowed paths.
- Relative includes are resolved from the current file and from configured include roots.
- Standard include roots such as /usr/include and /usr/local/include are considered automatically.
- Include cycles are detected and rejected.